No release amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a motion to amend the criminal code to abolish the provisions on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted.
The new rules, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, were rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic offences.
Mr Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for allegedly concluding a disadvantageous contract with Russia to buy natural gas.
The judgment is not yet final and the appeal of the convicts is due to be heard in December.
Mr Tymoshenko himself described the verdict as political revenge by the regime and the trial also raised suspicions in the West of the court's bias.
The motion to remove Article 365 from the Penal Code, which sentenced the former Prime Minister, was supported by 147 MPs.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals.
