The menu of an obese child: He doesn't eat breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children ages 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that children who are obese are more likely to come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This once again shows how important the environment in which a person grows up and the examples that surround him are for his healthy development.
The number of sausages on the tables of obese children is up to half that of families with normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had fries for dinner the day before the "Obesity is no accident" awareness campaign.
Sports are not a favorite activity in families with fat children, but they are also a favorite activity of the majority of today's students - only 15 percent said that their parents make time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of the school year last year, and almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic were interviewed.
This was the second year of the 'Obesity is no accident' campaign, supported by the National Health Insurance Fund and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grade have taken part in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are key factors in the alarming increase in children who are overweight or even obese.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed said that they ate breakfast-second-breakfast-lunch-vesper-dinner five times a day - one of the main requirements for a healthy diet", says one survey.
No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relatively small things, such as a regular family breakfast, are important for a child's healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of school families have breakfast.
- And in most families, everyone eats breakfast for themselves.
The worst was the finding that one in ten families does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey showed that families with overweight children are much more likely to eat unhealthy potatoes.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary sodas every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed participate in sports, fewer than half of their parents do so - only 15 percent.
Make your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own meal plan from the options offered according to appetite and opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 in terms of nutrition are far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite foods were many flour dishes, meat dishes, and of course sweets.
"The particular concern is the high popularity of sweet sodas", the final report on the survey stresses.
At lunch, the main course, pasta narrowly beat chicken.
The children were almost completely averse to vegetables and the popularity of fish and vegetables as lunch was also very low.
The return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if given the right information.
"In the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the 'obesity is not a coincidence' lecture, there was a significant shift in preferences towards healthy eating principles in many cases", the results of the project state.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet Limousines, where many children began to prefer ordinary water.
The children also had a much higher incidence of choosing poultry or fish as the main course of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweets.
Professionals say a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In my introductory article on how stylists learn, I had a little bit of a complaint that this was a little too much material to start with.
I had no idea what was coming.
Talks by three industry professionals, the clothing of problematic figures and a seminar on how to do it on the pitch.
It's supposed to get worse.
The closer the exam gets, the more information and practical tasks lie ahead.
But even if the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it is still full.
This time we debated with Director Alena (not a single man attends the course) how to dress a woman who does not have an ideal proportioned figure.
And that's most of us.
Some have a neck too short, others a figure too youthful without proper curves and still others are chubby.
It is the stylist's job to visually conceal wide shoulders, lengthen the neck, or conjure up the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a woman like Jennifer Lopez -- big breasts, wide hips, and a slim waist -- pretty and physically, without being too provocative.
For example, if the difference between waist and hips is so great that the skirt or pants really don't fit, at least one piece should be tailored.
You will not regret it, for well-fitting clothes are simply priceless.
Because a tailor-made skirt feels much better than one with a pole that is always too high and sliding, and that sticks out at the waist, etc.
Boyish figures, in turn, may allow themselves to wear clothing with wrinkles, bumps, applications, embroidery or braiding.
With all this information and character types, I'm glad I have a whole week to think it through.
And yet I'm afraid, given the homework, it's almost impossible to do.
Each of the students was assigned a celebrity to design a suitable outfit for her - a day dress and an evening gown.
We should take into account the current appearance, fashion style and figure of the star.
I'm supposed to dress up Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
I'm cheering inside, because that's much better for me personally than wearing Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has gained about 100 pounds lately (well, that's a little over the top), or even the young Selena Gomez.
The clothes are to be cut from magazines or searched on the Internet, printed, and then graphically edited.
The "Moodboard", as the whole result is called, is then to express our very personal style and our relationship with graphic design.
It is very important to think about the graphic side of styling.
The stylist not only physically attracts the models, but also designs the so-called product page in the magazines (according to specifications, for example trend handbags, coats, etc.).
We were told about it by the stylist and designer Mario Kameník.
But not until Sunday.
That means a stylist needs to have a good overall view.
The Saturday presentation, which was filled with information on figure types, was immediately spiced up by three industry visitors:
The designers are Jan Pokorný, Jakub Polanka and Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and that a stylist should be able to exploit this.
And a skilled stylist can work with a single garment in a variety of ways.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat over jeans as usual, like a T-shirt or a coat, but you can also wear it on your naked body, put heels on it and wear it as a dress.
You can just roll up your sleeve or your collar and the whole look will look completely different.
"Play with it", he insisted.
But the advice that came most to my mind was, "First, you must know the rules perfectly".
"Only then can you hurt her", said Jacob.
I finally understand why we have to dig through all these teaching, what you can combine with what and why, even though you often see something completely different in fashion magazines.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared many more clothing options than he ultimately photographs.
So for a ten-page fashion story, you have to be prepared to style at least fifteen.
And also that the clothes in the photo, when combined with other accessories, sometimes look very different from what they actually are.
So all of this is to be expected when designing the outfit.
Jan Pokorný confirmed that image and style are sometimes half the success.
You just have to look at Madonna, a not-so-brilliant singer whose image and marketing have made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the services of a stylist are generally reserved.
Even celebrities often consider this a waste of money (the main thing is that I bring something, how I look is secondary).
And if someone is getting styled, we should expect that he or she will probably force a size on us that is quite different (smaller) than what he or she actually needs.
Then you just have to Google it to see for sure that the tabloid press is writing that the celebrity has gained or lost weight, etc.
Jan and Mario encouraged us on Sunday not to think that a stylist should focus only on fashion and then "put together" the outfit.
In his work, he has to communicate with the people he styles and he has to be a skilled psychologist.
He's a man who can judge people without offering his opinion.
"If some manager asks us to sift through her closet and add some pretty pieces, we can't just take her out of the closet and say, 'Oh, my God, that's terrible.'"
"You have to find at least a few things that are commendable to recommend, things that you can contribute to", says Mario.
He also showed us very specifically what a so-called "place bag" must contain.
So a bag that you button up around your waist and carry all the necessary possessions around with you.
In addition to clear items such as scissors, hair-removal rollers, and safety pins, it also contains utensils such as a nylon thread (to help the stylist photograph products such as handbags or hats), special clips to grab the clothing from behind if it is too large (needles or other clamps are not allowed to prevent the fabric from breaking), and, of course, sewing.
But in order to not only listen but also try something practical, we learned how to properly glue shoes together.
Even when you're shooting in a studio where the floor is flat, you can damage the sole of your shoe, let alone the outside one.
We were glued and glued...
You can't even touch the shoes with the scissors, or they'll break.
So you really have to be clever.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without restriction.
I'm not exactly a man of skill.
All of this was only a fraction of what we heard at the second weekend of the continuation course.
One thing I've learned is that it's not easy to be a professional stylist.
V Need for Speed: The Run - the illegal race across America
The review
The initially carefree drive is transformed from a routine drive to the early shift by a series of entirely avoidable, amateurish mistakes.
The Commission has been able to achieve a large part of its ambitions, but what good is that if nobody seems to want to do more?
Even before it hit the store shelves, the new installment, subtitled "The Run", raised high expectations.
He promised to take the aging Need for Speed series to a new level, and in the playable demo examples, it actually seemed to be more than just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious to see how the adapted passages were, where the main character gets out of the car and walks on.
But as you're used to with NFS, the end result is a lot different than you expected.
- Sure, potentially they're pretty decent arcade races, but overall the game is dwarfed by some unnecessary bugs that have been present in this series more or less for a few years now.
So they're not really errors anymore, but rather signs of basically incomprehensible laziness on the part of game developers.
The adventure is off to a very good start.
First introduced to the story, the main character Jack has some personal character problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the West Coast, you get behind the wheel, with the task of being the first to New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is run on a different track and that each stage takes place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don't get the impression for a moment that the game is going to offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very pretty, although the technical level of the graphics is not higher than the previous parts of the series.
So nothing that's going to change the world.
But driving through the desert, through autumn landscapes, or high up through deep snow landscapes is visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, unusual elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, a desert storm can be a surprise, severely limiting your view.
In the mountains, you have to be hell-bent on not being swept away by an avalanche.
Besides, the individual races are quite well arranged.
A few, but enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the clock), then you are waiting for a personal duel with a single opponent.
And then the police get involved, trying to screw you over.
One thing that's new is the passages where Jack leaves the car.
It's more of an interactive animation where Jack is running from someone and the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, however, there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (only three in particular).
In the end, this is more to the advantage, because at least this element has no chance of becoming boring - it is one of the elements that make the game more varied in the context of the above.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
I would like to say that, from today's point of view, while it is not uprooting trees, on the other hand, you could not say that it is bad.
If you're looking for realistic simulations, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model still does a good job of driving the action-packed car, even though the competition could do better.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems only come up after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model isn't entirely OK.
It's hard to expect a game like this to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how the car behaves before you hit any object, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When passing close or passing oncoming cars, in some places you "slip" the other car only slightly, but in other, almost identical situations you get into a slide and spin wildly.
Or the car's about to go to pieces.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter anymore, but it's always annoying.
The restarts are solved this way: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue point of the track.
- Only in every race you only have five restarts.
Once you've used them all, you start all over again.
So the restarts are more like a tool in case something goes wrong, but you shouldn't rely on them.
Sometimes even a restart doesn't help, and the only thing that helps is to memorize the critical section.
The most unpleasant thing is that the same things happen often in the same places.
For example, some curves have to be done in a very specific way, otherwise you just can't get through.
In other places, you will always find "civilian" cars in the same configuration, whether you are first or fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see your opponent playing past two cars coming towards you, but by the time you get there, the cars are already in a position where you have to overtake or brake.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed to get to this situation right in front of you.
The counterparties have other advantages.
There are a few places in the game where you're always overtaken in the same place by the same opponent, and here again regardless of the time.
The craziest thing is this, at the end of the game, on the long bridge, which you cross in the opposite direction.
The opponent has to overtake someone who's obviously coming out of hell.
And then once it's in front of you, it's obviously going to take your view, so you start out with your car in a bunch a few times.
- Sure, you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but that intention is so clear that it quickly robs you of the pleasure of the game.
And that's a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is overall quite entertaining and in places so action-packed that you almost don't know where your head is.
And it doesn't matter what the "fault" is - the concept of 50 unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something else entirely...
Another unusual idea is the change of car during the race.
The gas stations on the track must not be overlooked, because this is where you can change cars, although in most cases the car you have now is sufficient.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American sedans for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical drives, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the story mode, there is also the task mode (challenges) - the races in the individual locations known from the story.
Here, not only are there medals, but also experience points to gain for your own profile, which is shared for the tasks (challenges) and the story.
To get to the higher level of the driver, various objects must be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also linked to the online Autolog function, which compares one's own results with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
Another of the incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you drive into a subway tunnel (because of me) and you ride the tracks in the dark (because of me).
The speedometer shows a speed of 150 to 200 kilometers per hour (because of me), but then suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you to the scrap yard.
I think we're gonna be debating for a long time in our office whether this was a blackout by the game designers or whether the writers think we're that stupid.
The technical side is not overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and even brilliant here and there.
What's even more annoying is that in some exciting moments, the repetition rate slows down, and sometimes quite dramatically.
This is particularly true of accidents involving a large number of people, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is fine as far as I'm concerned and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a broad range of younger audiences, a soundtrack was created "from everyone something" - but who buys such a game for the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run?
If the game hadn't been reduced by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned, we could have said with the breast of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But it kind of makes the game look unfinished.
It's a pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared to be stung by these bugs with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with choirs of Charles University
The Festival Festa Academica is now offering for the third time the linking of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this with musical experience.
During the festival, the twenty professional and university choirs will introduce themselves.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that will take place on November 17.
"Charles University is a big part of the festival".
"The participants include the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, and the festival committee includes the Rector Václav Hampl", said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organising team.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of vocational school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme includes the composition of the important Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening, the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place in the halls of the People's House in Vinohrady, which also features university choirs, including those of Charles University.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day and the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music at the highest level to the public and to promote the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organiser is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The event was co-sponsored by Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of Prague, and Václav Hampl, the rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The programme includes, apart from festival concerts, numerous musical meetings, student events, matinees and other events.
The festival is organised by the European Film Academy (EFTA) and is organised by the European Film Council (EFTA).
The EU Ambassador Vicenová said:
The Czechs have a reputation for being pessimistic and Eurosceptic
"The Lisbon Treaty has brought about a tangible shift in the balance between the various institutions".
I did not expect such a hard war to break out".
"It will take five or six years for the tide to settle and for everyone to get used to their new role", Milena Vicenová, the Czech ambassador to the European Union, began her lecture at the Law School rather sharply.
She showed how seriously she takes the motto 'Comprehensible and open about Europe' in the first part of her talk, in which she managed to describe the various EU institutions and their relations with each other in such a comprehensible and understandable way that she could have envied so many lecturers at the Faculty of Law of Charles University.
She also praised the new Permanent President of the Council of Europe, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, criticism was loud that he was too inconspicuous - a gray official not fit for such a role, but I must say that it took everyone's breath away how well he handled the matter.
"He is a man who is able to listen patiently to 27 Member States, to communicate with them and, above all, to have clear ideas about how the EU should proceed.
She then explained that the new position of the High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy was an answer to the question: Who is this - the European Union?
No one wants to ban us from our oil caps quarrel
