The Czech presidency of two years ago was a success, she said.
The Czech Republic had overcome the financial and gas crises and also hosted the Eastern Partnership Summit.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
The Ambassador said that not only during the Presidency but also during the crisis that followed it, which has not yet been overcome, things were quite hectic.
And the EU's seven-year budget still needs to be approved, which makes things much more complicated given the current economic situation.
The Commission is also proposing a budget for the period from 1 January to 31 December.
The Ambassador also recalls her own slogans with which she came to Brussels: 'Understandable about Europe'.
"If there's one thing I don't like, it's creepy abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that nobody understands.
How can I as a citizen know whether Brussels is really making up curvy or round cucumbers and bananas of different sizes or whether someone is actually trying to ban us from quarrelling?
It would also like to use the EU's soil to get more Czechs into European institutions.
Europe of two or different speeds in the future
The EU Ambassador believes that the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics, who perceive the negative rather than the positive aspects of the matter.
The Czech representation in the European institutions is all the more disturbing.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect, including the proposal for a directive on the approximation of the laws of the Member States relating to the labelling of foodstuffs.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group, the so-called V4.
"Believe me, if a Pole or a Hungarian comes to me and a Slovak is nearby, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what are you guys doing, sticking your heads together - is that your V4 again?'
The Commission is also proposing to increase the number of EU citizens who are eligible for EU funding.
It sees the concept of a Europe of two or even different speeds as much more real than a 'European federation'.
"We have the countries of the eurozone and the countries outside the eurozone.
"We have the Schengen area and we already have the institution of enhanced cooperation".
"For the first time, it was said that only those countries should cooperate that want to and those that do not should stand aside".
'There will be more and more of these institutions, which will ultimately lead to a strong 'Europe of different speeds'', she expects.
It also welcomed the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuyes in enforcing the principle that all issues affecting the EU as a whole must be discussed by all Member States and not just by the euro area countries.
Brand story:
Innovator IBM enters its second century
If you were to look for a word that best describes IBM's strategy, it would be "longevity".
IBM is synonymous with the technological revolution for the general public, and is known as a modern company, although it has been around for a century.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by its first head, the visionary Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He was already advocating the slogan that countless global problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" became the trademark around which the life of the future giant was to unfold (and at the same time the title of the company's internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
This was also the basis of the company culture that Watsen had prepared thoroughly.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a century because it stayed true to its principles and didn't shy away from changing everything else around it.
And that allowed us to transform technology, business and society in our first century.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director, in celebration of the anniversary.
A thoughtful system
Watson was already providing social welfare for his employees in the 1930s - similar to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: IBM employees were among the first American employees to have paid leave, insurance from the employer plus elegant work uniforms and a well-thought-out remuneration system for the best innovators and traders.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
