Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporttourist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West only selected ones were allowed.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (GDR), the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea, and Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was also allowed, when Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A major paradox of the socialist era was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of the CSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, for example, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, travel agencies offered tours to the West, but then you had to accept huge lines or sleep in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter was far from settled.
The so-called currency pledge - the condition for leaving for the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a currency bond it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, so it is no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend homes and cottages - a practice that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a Czech travel revolution.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which is no longer even recognized today, is the fact that the most popular holiday destination for Czechs - Croatia - was not even accessible until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 1990s, the currency obligation in the neighbouring countries of Western Europe was abolished, which led to a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
This is how Czech holidaymakers slept in a park tent on trips to Paris, because who could afford a hotel or a boarding house back then?
A typical feature of foreign travel by Czechs at that time was a suitcase packed with canned goods, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech króna - after decades, our tourists could finally freely buy Western currency.
Our living standards and, as a result, our average wages rose, which ushered in another important moment in 1997.
The increase in demand for travel led travel agents to start preparing for regular charter flights after 1997, which made air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already had currencyless payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-vintage travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand - was booked due to high demand.
Since then, direct charter flights carrying Czech passengers have been flying to sunny countries far away every year, and this year, 12 exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
Hundreds of thousands of Czechs travel to exotic countries every year.
Another significant moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday including the cost of the holiday destination.
