The most beautiful swimming pools in Europe
♪ Jump into the blue ♪
By Julia Stanek
Swimming pools with UFO sights, and swimming pools in Budapest: Travelers in Europe can experience the wonders of the blue - and after a city tour or a hike, rest their tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the last year and a half, she couldn't miss one thing in her luggage: her bathing suit.
Lying back on the water, she looked up at the ornate domes, swam toward marble pits waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
If she liked a bathroom, she would quickly write it down in her notebook - including interesting details about the building's design and history.
More than 200 swimming pools were explored in this way by architectural historian Meder - and she now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": popular swimming pools in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
She travelled through 13 countries on her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She says she doesn't have much of a problem with sports - only in the water.
The only annoyance is that swimming enthusiasts have to deal with blue tiles and chlorine fumes while joggers can breathe in the enchanting scent of pine forests or listen to the joyful song of birds in the park.
"I wondered one day why swimming pools always have to be so ugly", says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths".
Water surface area doubled Architecture
The reason for the high well-being factor in baths is that all the senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders put in the effort, swimming pools can be a delight: "In place of a floor, you have a surface of water in baths".
"It's transparent on the one hand, but it also reflects the beauty of the entire building".
Everything is visually doubled: high vaults, colorful tiles, jump boards.
The small-format picture book "Badefreuden" contains 190 pages of information on the architectural and cultural history of historic spa oases - but above all it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent thermal baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing body of water in a rugged karst cave (Cave Bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many heated outdoor baths in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views. While the Zurich rooftop bath offers a view of the entire city, the outdoor pool of a St. Anton bath can be used to gaze out over the snow-covered Arlberg - and the steam room has a window from which you can watch the traffic on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most unusual design of the pool awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that just landed in the Alps.
Three open bowls evaporate in winter, while the mountains of the Oetzel valley rise to the sky in the background.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not every pool the pool collector went to got the smell of chlorine up her nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, and the Árpád bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells so badly of heating oil that it is hard to believe it has landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrocarbonated healing water, which is almost black and its glue sticks to your skin as soon as you slide into the pool - a unique wellness experience.
But Iris Meder's search for beautiful bathing sites was disappointing in one place: When she tried to visit the outdoor and sunbathing area in Bad Luhatschowitz, Czech Republic, she found a fenced-in area.
The bathhouse, designed in 1902 by architect Dušan Jurkovic, has since been closed.
As Meder peered through the weathered windows of the red, white, and yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
The decay was counteracted by a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
This bath has already undergone three phases of construction, and you can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating from its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the style of the Alhambra, added around 1900.
Since the careful modernisation in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originally came from the Black Forest.
"It is an achievement to combine so many different styles of building into one great unit", says Meder.
In a palace like this, the immersion in the thermal pool is obviously just a side thing.
Agricultural speculation
Deutsche Bank is running a raw material review
By Christian Teevs
Is Deutsche Bank giving up its agricultural commodity business?
According to SPIEGEL-ONLINE, Josef Ackermann has commissioned a working group to study the effects of speculation on the world's poor.
In January, the CEO wants to draw consequences.
