According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international task force is currently investigating the allegations in the Foodwatch report.
The results of the audit are expected to be presented to the Deutsche Bank Board of Management by the end of the year, with a recommendation on how to deal with it.
The Bank's management will then announce its consequences at the end of January.
The result could be a reduction in raw material trade, or even a complete reversal.
Ackermann is tinkering with his image
Foodwatch's chief executive, Thilo Bode, welcomed the news but reiterated his criticism of the financial industry: "The bet on rising food prices is a particularly stark illustration of how ruthless banks are hurting the common good today".
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
"Deutsche Bank must remove from its portfolio all investments where money is used to bet on food prices", Bode said.
"Whether it's about starving people or the reputation of Deutsche Bank".
Ackermann's insight is surprising at first glance, but it is clear that the CEO wants to present a perfect image a few months before leaving office.
On Monday, Deutsche Bank announced that the CEO will not be moving to the supervisory board as planned.
By abandoning the controversial agricultural speculation, he could improve his image.
And he hardly cares about the potential losses - after all, his successor would have to deal with them.
One in two would quit raw material plants
Foodwatch is trying to keep the pressure on the manager high.
