Only 11 percent of respondents consider it legitimate for Deutsche Bank to offer investments that bet on food prices.
Many bank customers would also face personal consequences if they knew their bank was involved in such transactions: one in two would abandon all investments that invest in commodity speculation, the survey found.
Forty-three percent would advise acquaintances against such a bank, and 49 percent said they would consider terminating their account and moving to another institution.
21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural story with ups and downs and a happy ending: the Austrian pavilion at the 1958 Brussels World's Fair won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and disappeared.
Now it's being reopened as an exhibition hall.
If modern postwar architecture is to be admired, with its clear forms, glass halls, bold curves and new building materials, which are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion designed by architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition is a fitting and famous example.
Schwanzers Pavilion won the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight, floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he built the Austrian Pavilion at the next World Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bullet-shaped side-building in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Station, converted and opened a 20th-century museum in 1962 - it was called the "20th House".
But the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls to hang the art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna found a new home.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and falling down.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has renovated the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, which owns the house, opens its first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every way.
The new beginning has been carried through by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a doctorate in art history with a notable career as a figure skater in her youth, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Salzburg, pushed through the conversion with political and historical preservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship money and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the eponymous foundation, a café and a bookstore were to be built, and an office building was to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krishnanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensibly rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but also because he had studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was a "tremendously important place" for him, where he had looked at the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
The current renovation had far greater problems: The building was "a waste of energy", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, fibreglass reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Steel beams for cold bridges have been reinforced or replaced and asbestos-filled ceilings have been repaired.
Two basements made room for the new use, a low light pit between the house and the street provides exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust-proof paint.
And the theater is still exactly as it was.
And all under strict supervision of the Antiquities Authority and with a small budget.
"Often, we had to find a good, cheap material that the Heritage Board liked", says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
It was difficult with the pavilion, which "came from Brussels", Krischanitz said recently, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and yet it wants to "raise a right consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because it has been a case of urban luck: around the Swiss Garden is being built the completely newly planned "Mainbahnhofquartier", with office and residential buildings.
And another lucky breakthrough may yet come: the 21st house could get reinforcements from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle, and as we hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss garden.
