And he will take over as chairman of the board in May - not just in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
It's going to be hard for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, but rather a professor of economics and a central banker and would certainly have needed some time to get used to it.
He then takes over the strategy of a bank that has just proved once again that it has long since earned the title of Europe's biggest scandal bank.
Because UBS is huge on the one hand - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other hand it has been slipping from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing seems to be spared the once-proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of a quiet, solid but also a brash Swiss wealth manager with ambitious goals: she wanted to become a big name in investment banking.
So in 2007, UBS, on the one hand, managed $1.6 trillion more money from high net worth clients than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, it had advanced as an investment bank into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That was impressive.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later a longtime professor of banking in Zurich, says: "I always presented UBS to my students as a model of a good bank".
"Looking back now, you wonder how I could have been so wrong".
He was wrong.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something was seriously wrong with UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli, who had been considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker, unexpectedly resigned.
A few months later, they figured out why he left.
The bank's investment arm had been bogged down with subprime debt and had to write off billions.
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase of 13 billion francs.
It did find investors, but some that some would have been surprised to hear about until recently: an opaque Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign wealth fund so secretive that its name was not even known.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to announce new billions of losses, and its chairman Marcel Ospel, still the second highest paid member of the board of directors in Switzerland in 2006, resigned.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: UBS was on the verge of collapse due to its misinvestments in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of troubled securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced conversion loan, through which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because it realized how dramatic it is for a small country to have such large banks.
Finally, UBS' balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times the size of the Swiss economy (see chart).
"Once again, we could not save UBS", says bank researcher Geiger.
