It also agreed to pay $780 million in restitution for unjust profits from these transactions, including penalties.
UBS thus more or less openly admitted to having helped to avoid tax.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the race for rich clients: the umbrella of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was not the same.
The resignation of the CEO and the Chairman of the Board of Directors followed.
And the exodus of client funds.
The Bank had lost its credibility in two key areas of business within a few months: investment banking through mis-speculation and asset management through aid for tax evasion.
And just when things were getting a little quieter, just when you thought UBS was going to get it right, this unfortunate dealer story follows: A single dealer is ripping off 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes something is wrong.
