The buildings here are magnificent, the rents of the shops are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers like Tiffany's can be found here among traditional Swiss shops like the Confiserie Sprüngli.
For centuries, it has been the home of Swiss banks, from the National Bank to the Credit Suisse Palace to elite private banks like Julius Baer.
The reception hall of UBS is entered through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are clad in marble, fronted by thick leather chairs, and next to the bank's logo, a large sign that says "Safe".
UBS knows what the customer wants here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank was eventually displaced by both the large Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse - or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, because he, like all Swiss bankers, also does business with the two big banks.
He believes that UBS has become too big - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also expanded.
The Swiss would have nothing to say there.
"And if they did, they must have long since adapted to the Anglo-Saxon ways".
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that transformed UBS, first bringing it high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss major bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became apparent.
"That Wednesday, the coalition government of the small country of seven million decided on the largest bailout in the history of its nation", writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
The politicians allocated up to 68 billion francs, or about 45 billion euros, to save the bankrupt big bank.
How did this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged to form a huge group.
