Peter Englund's new book, "Beauty and Horror: A History of the First World War, Told in Nineteen Fates", begins with a long list of key characters that touch your heart.
Here's a tip: Carefully cut out this page and make it your bookmark.
You'll get to know these people very well in Englund's novel, and these main characters will act as your GPS, as a beacon in those few moments when you, like Englund's men and women, are lost in the fog of war and stripped of your illusions.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which decides the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote an unusual book that he describes not unfairly as "a work of anti-history".
It contains few big names, no important contracts, no famous battles, no ambassadors, no angry reporters, no discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is less a book about what happened, he explains, but rather "a book about how it was".
"Beauty and Horror" is almost the wartime experiences of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and office workers.
Some of these people are going to be heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad, or die.
Each of these lives flickers like votive candles in a church, some add up while others go out.
Englund's book differs from the usual history books.
It also corrects the notion that World War I was just the devastating post war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and the Beast" explores other war zones with expertise: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are falling beehives, one is celebrating Christmas under the pyramids in Egypt, tsetse flies are an unsolvable problem.
This is a moving book almost from the start.
War floods these people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling like Kordite.
Imagine you're a woman at home with her children and you hear cannon fire in the distance.
Who's coming, anyway?
Hardly anyone understands what's happening or why this war is being waged in the first place.
"Falling facts", notes Englund, "were furnished with conjecture, assumption, hope, fear, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and the Beast" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German sailor.
Their stories were mainly taken from memories, letters and other material already published.
Their life stories can be frightening or poignant, but they are extremely vivid in the englunds of the collection of small moments lost in detail.
Many of them are about scarcity and self-care.
In the story of a German schoolgirl, he says: "Substitute, substitute everywhere".
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, fake eraser, paper bands, wooden buttons, and so on".
He's telling us more about the alternative food in Germany.
It describes "meat made from pressed rice and baked in ram fat (and served last with a false wooden bone), tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes that were sewn with wood".
He notes that "there were 837 registered food substitutes allowed in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
Recognizing his own drive for savagery, one American says of war: "You feel that, after all, this is what was meant for men rather than sitting in the armchair with the evening paper or the best-seller and a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, pretending that such a facade means civilization and that there is no barbarism behind one's strengthened and patched shirt chest".
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he will probably die and no one will notice or care.
"When you put off the idea of self-sacrifice, you want to think that it's happening in front of an audience", he writes.
Instead, it is as terrible as "a condemned man who was hanged in secret".
Other observations concern the old Europe falling apart and new forms of terror.
"The conflict became increasingly an economic contest", writes Englund, "a war between factories".
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the younger century": "the word-savvy and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a suit who slaughters while sitting at a desk".
People behave in unpredictable ways, and there are frivolous behaviors as well as heroic ones.
Englund discusses the soldiers who actively tried to contract an venereal disease from a prostitute in order to escape frontline service.
"The grotesque expression of this can be found in the trade in gonorrhoea pus, for soldiers bought and smeared themselves on their genitals in the hope of getting into the hospital", he writes.
"Those who were really desperate rubbed him in the eyes, which left them blind for the rest of their lives".
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Englund's poetry becomes fluid and yet unobtrusive, perfectly adapting to his human task.
