Walls have eyes: How researchers are watching you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many young men who posted their anti-immigration opinions online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to committing a shooting in Norway in July that killed 77 people, had his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time in front of his computer before his attack and chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's concealment of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply have to use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or a new diet product, the ads invited users to a survey asking about their education level, their attitudes toward violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to poll more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave their offices.
"It's a fairly new research method", says Bartlett.
Some of the findings are hardly surprising: online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male, and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens".
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a hot new tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends like likes, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has seen the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title increase by almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you wouldn't normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"In the past, when you tried to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have let them in", says Bartlett.
"With Facebook, all that's gone - you go straight to them".
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunkenness on Facebook were significantly more likely to have a drinking problem than students who kept quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that peers, such as residential counselors, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it", said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We've found a way to identify vulnerable children who otherwise would not have been found".
Facebook is also constantly tapping into the data of its own population.
The site's data team compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to - masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its vast data mine available to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want to or not, and to play Scrabble with a friend who's thousands of miles away, you allow the site to post your personal information.
But what if Facebook users are part of a survey that they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines for how they collect their data offline, online, everything is allowed.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study that examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she was concerned, it was all about her and her friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that a research participant is completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know how much of what's on a user profile and in posts is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things", says Selwyn.
So Selwyn, despite his years as a technology researcher, still thinks that a clipboard and a pen are the best research tools anyone can use.
"There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
"Social research has to deal with the social - and a lot of social life still happens offline".
