In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Professional Idiot" about the rise of the personal computer, and he sat down with Jobs for over an hour, in which they had one of the rarest, most detailed conversations.
By this time, it had been over 10 years since Jobs had been kicked out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, and looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in Expert Idiots, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing from the delivery.
It wasn't until after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the principal's garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which will hit theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to loathe long interviews, Jobs here appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
Four times during the interview, there are long pauses between question and answer -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes into play, when he seems impatient to respond to Cringley's questions, prompting him to respond more quickly to issues or side-acts of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, The Lost Interview seems kind of incredibly far-sighted, as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing that he thinks is right or wrong and represents his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read postmortem tributes to Jobs' career, but to see Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the leap to greatness is something entirely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
And as soon as he did all this, he went and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences from the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"In all my years in business, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's just how it's done.'
Nobody knows why he does what he does, and nobody in the business really thinks things through.
I've noticed that.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Amazed at how costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs" that were quantified on a mere assumption and then adjusted with "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was charged:
Jobs tells us about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed you to sneak into the telephone company and make long distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs' enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while scrambling through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent stuff around the world half a dozen times, and if you were to ring the phone, it would come out a minute later on the phone next door", Jobs says, laughing.
"We were young and we learned that we could build something ourselves that could control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We both didn't know much, but we could build this little thing that could control a giant thing, and that was an incredible lesson, and I don't think there would be an Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to talk about a glorious prank that he and Wozniak almost pulled when they called the Vatican in the middle of the night through the Blue Box and wanted to talk to the Pope while doing their best to mimic Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope answered the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called Bill Hewlett unprepared):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views of what a company was and how well it treated its employees".
Later, Jobs became one of the HP employees who visited the company's Palo Alto research labs, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
He was the size of a suitcase, had a little screen with a brown tube, and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he was installing some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the argument going through the roof... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer".
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for 15 dollars, which was incredibly believable.
The big companies that are declining:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants would stumble with their visions and lose control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copier or printer, so what?"
They have a monopoly on the stock, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [are they] the people who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is being eradicated by people who have no concept of good products versus bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger, you could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
You've suffered defeat from victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop that great idea, it changes and grows".
You learn a lot about his subtleties.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to memorize 5,000 things, these concepts, and put them all together...
At the end of the day, it's all about taste, it's all about trying to take the best stuff that people have ever made and then trying to put those things together into what you're making.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We're always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made the Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for the computer industry, they would be doing fantastic things in other fields.
