How to Uncover a Lie
A glance at the current headlines shows how serious and widespread deception and lying are in our daily lives.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy dealing with sexual harassment allegations from several women, both sides accusing each other of lying.
Penn State officials are facing charges of perjury for allegedly withholding reports of a retired football coach sexually abusing a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was heard over an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton set off when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories of cheating in school and college exams are common.
There have been instances where teachers have given their students the answers to the examinations so that they themselves would do well on their own performance checks.
Mentors who are supposed to teach the opposite are sending a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception are we witnessing?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
But many of these lies are considered to be necessity lies.
Another study found that strangers lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Lying is something that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game, such as charades, in which the goal is to shout "Have a good time", the disguise of deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stutter, blush and flap.
But this does not mean that these liars are hard to uncover and expose.
A skilled lie detector can penetrate the truth by learning about the structure of the assertion, the subtle facial expressions, questioning and timing.
I've spent several years studying the scientific findings of the vast and ever-growing field of deception, and it's clear that deception deception is a modern skill that's easy to learn and helps us navigate our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or managing is one of your professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at evaluating other people, getting their interest, and controlling their own emotions.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more self-centered lies than women, whose lies are more "other-centered" - usually to protect others' feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as a criminal, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know when someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of that person.
It's called baseline, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent assessment of changes.
Watch the posture, the laughter, the quality of their voice.
You should know better when someone usually keeps kicking so that you don't wrongly accuse them of kicking during a meeting.
Then watch for accumulations of noticeable verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Think of these clumps as alarm bells that are squealing, not as evidence of disguise.
People who cheat may freeze up when they try to remember their story, they may point their feet toward the door or lean toward the exit, change their position in a significant way, or show a "post-interview relaxation", that deep, relaxing exhalation and change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Interviewers often mistakenly signal that a job interview is over, only to find that relaxation after the job interview.
Also, watch your subject's language.
Scott Peterson's runaway is famous for using the past tense when he claimed his murdered wife was still alive, triggering a national manhunt.
Deceivers may also use distant language, such as "I did not have a sexual relationship with this woman, Miss Lewinsky", or repeating a tricky question in its entirety.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience".
This makes the response perceptual rather than objective, often sounding the alarm.
There is no magic cure for unmasking lies, but you can learn skills that make unmasking possible.
These skills can help you to reduce the risk of being a victim of fraud in your personal and professional life.
