The court approves the switch to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The switchover from analogue to digital signals is one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional complaints filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which requires the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes needed to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the switch to digital terrestrial television.
The decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate, as it did not obtain the necessary qualified majority of eight votes for the court to decide on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality.
The draft lawsuit, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional because the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel) is responsible for regulating radio and television, and the decree would therefore be contrary to hierarchical principles and legal requirements.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted in favour of the project.
The Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the decree-law, which, after the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero stopped applying the decree-law and stopped all activities to establish digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister expressed his disagreement with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Land government could not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration by general regulations.
"I also do not believe that doing so would undermine the independence of the regulatory body", she said, noting that the central government is constitutionally responsible for planning strategic policy areas such as the telecommunications sector, as it directs national affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital ones is one of the most important changes that has taken place in the world in recent years, and it results in better use of the radio spectrum, improved signal quality and more channels.
The Commission's proposal to introduce a new system for the exchange of information on the European Union's external relations is a step in the right direction.
These matters, she stressed, "require the action of the whole system, according to the principle of economic management by the state, they contain a set of features that place the constitution in the hands of the central government".
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital transition through government, despite having highly specialized institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government interfered with the powers of Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be respected", she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán individually is being considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor election is almost 27 percent, with 879 out of a total of 6074 votes still to be counted.
The possibility of single counting of ballots is a reality in this year's elections in Michoacán, as the difference between first and second place in the governor's elections is almost 27 percent, according to data released by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), with 879 out of a total of 6074 votes still to be counted.
In this context, the President of the General Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that on 9 November the electoral authority had adopted a series of regulations to harmonize local regulations with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted its political constitution, its electoral law or its electoral justice law to the reforms passed by Congress, so that they did not come into force in this election round.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislature, declaring the vote of the State Commissioner on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal" because the latter does not have the right to "decide or veto it".
In an interview on the possibility of single counting, María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM would allow the local electoral authority to count the ballots partially or completely.
The results of the votes in the minutes are not the same; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not in the file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of completed ballots may be counted if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the runner-up of less than one per cent, provided that the party or coalition leader who is the second of the candidates mentioned makes an explicit request at the beginning of the meeting.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, after the final counting, it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one per cent, provided that a representative of the party whose candidate came second has expressly requested this.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where according to PREP the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral minutes have not yet been counted.
