The formation of the new Italian government on Wednesday
The new Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present him with the new government to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The new Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present him with the new government to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president of the country, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is assumed that he will present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
The European Union has a responsibility to ensure that the EU's foreign policy is implemented in a way that is consistent with the principles of the European Union.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times", the former EU Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments suggest that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The frame is now well fixed", he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than usual, while Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to unbearable levels.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must pass a tough austerity package demanded by European politicians to restore the battered confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti to act quickly was compounded by the volatile market situation, which has led to the imposition of a 7% interest rate on Italian government bonds for 10 years, similar to the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Confindustria, the Italian industry association, told the press after meeting Monti: "We said we would support this government with all our might".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Montis' chances of success were greatly increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which resigned on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are aimed at achieving good results", said Angelino Alfano, Secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is essential because so far many of its members have spoken out against a government made up of mostly technocrats, which Monti is currently forming.
Support from Parliament
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the likely unpopular austerity measures.
Opposition to his efforts or delay in reforms could again trigger a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also pressing the issue by saying that a failure of Montis would be a disaster.
Monti began his debates on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' associations, as well as youth and women's organisations.
The Commission is now in the process of adopting a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has launched an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week when it was announced that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian government bonds have again reached critical limits due to uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
A rescue of Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government would have to wait until the next election, expected in 2013, despite predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement reforms rather than prefer elections.
Monti said he would like to have politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist it should be technicians only, a sign of their concerns about the process imposed by financial market pressure.
Political sources point out that the mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties make it difficult to involve people from political life.
