The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its twentieth anniversary.
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament says the band is prepared to play one of their best shows at the National Stadium next Sunday.
They've been waiting for over 20 years, but the band assures them that playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This was confirmed by the bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is on the South American leg of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the interview, which is available in full in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, Pearl Jam playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true: do you realize what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only the second time we've played in South and Central America, and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for vacation. It's such a beautiful country that we'll probably stay there for a few more days.
It's exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are totally devoted to the days leading up to the concert.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being there for us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people even think your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put a little pressure on you from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we've put on in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We played a couple of big shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they've made us ready for this gig in Costa Rica.
Really, we're in the mood to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing, and we love the jungle, and Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world for that.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surf waves?
A lot of our friends are surfers, and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends used to go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, and along with Mexico, they're great places to surf, and that's how we learned about people who love surfing.
Looking back on the tour, you guys put on some big shows with a lot of songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
We've never played there before, so we don't have any limits.
We're going to try to put on the best show we can with a lot of different songs, and we want to play a few songs from each album and give our fans a good and varied repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everybody likes a different song, so it's not easy to decide which one we're going to play.
If we add two or three songs that we haven't played in a while to our repertoire, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked those songs. Otherwise, they might be forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and I think it makes it more interesting for the audience.
This tour is your 20th anniversary.
Looking back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years.
We continue to count on this blessing and are thrilled to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and we're passionate about making music.
We're lucky to be able to go to the places in the world we've always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to be an active participant in the birth of grunge?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We're good friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising and quite unusual when a movement comes from a group of friends.
Occasionally a band comes out of a city, but it is quite unusual for five or ten groups to come out of the same city at the same time.
We're proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on tour, and we're still excited to be friends with all of them and honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It's also very unusual for a band like yours to stay with the same musicians for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt [Cameron] joined us 13 years ago, which alone is way longer than most bands last.
First of all, I think we all consider ourselves lucky to be alive and also we care about each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other and their music.
Your relationship with fame wasn't always easy, but on the other hand, your success allowed you to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure we don't go on tour too much, because it's too easy to get caught up in this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it brought to life, not obsess about being a famous rock star.
What are your memories of your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for three years, never released a record until Andy's death.
We were disappointed that it took so long, and we're still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started the band with us, and when I hear a song or see a photo, I think about what an amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas are responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yeah, the production team sent us videos of several bands and we liked this band the best, so we're curious to see what Las Robertas has to offer live.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed, I have no idea.
He's singing it, and I think he's singing the first thing that comes to mind.
Who was your bass player?
Of so many
Some of the first people I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them, I could spend the whole afternoon talking about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge alive even though it's no longer a fad?
I think we all don't feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time, and if they're still relevant today, I think that's great, because it's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making better music than ever before.
Her music was darker at first, now it's more positive.
Why? Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little light-hearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, even though they have something positive about them.
I was both moved to tears when I heard Ed play it.
I think when you get older and something traumatic happens in your life, like losing a family member or a friend, it affects your artistic creation and your music, and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also think you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
