An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and comprising several ministers and businessmen will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón, which the Uruguayan president says will be the highlight of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the Uruguayan community in Mexico.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón's support over the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries which still act as tax havens.
Mexico has been the chair of the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries.
The Uruguay government has in recent years sought to accelerate the concretization of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the OECD's 'grey list' of countries that have not adopted all international standards for tax cooperation.
On the commercial side, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004 and has contributed to an increase in trade between the two countries.
The mustachioed plumber enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land", he fights for the girl's love in stereo technology.
The game, which will hit stores around the world this month, was designed from the outset to match the features of the Ninth 3DS handheld console, which allows for 3D play without special glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to tell how stereoscopy works without glasses", said Omar Álvarez, the head of Nintendo's press in Spain, at the launch of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first video game from Nintendo that has been developed from the ground up for this console" because until now, successful titles like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of already existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesman emphasized that although it is three-dimensional, Super Mario 3D Land is an "affordable" video game that allows for fast, fluid play.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: the first part is "easy" to capture the less skilled users.
Afterwards, the experts can play a "second round" of the various levels of the game, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
The gameplay is also very simple, with the user being able to choose between an aggressive D or one that only affects the depth of the action, but the gameplay must always be three-dimensional to overcome the obstacles without falling victim to the visual effects.
This trip of Super Mario to the three-dimensional world also means the return of the figure to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo is winking at fans of the saga and repeating the recipe for success of the last issues: the mustachioed installer must overcome platforms full of dangers to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters new moves, environments, costumes, enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom guarantees the extradition of Portillos to the United States
Guatemala's President, Álvaro Colom, announced on Tuesday that he would allow the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo to face charges in the United States for conspiracy to launder $70 million.
This concludes the process of the US request for the extradition of Portillo so that he can be tried there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the government, given that an ordering court had already ordered extradition.
He stressed that during his administration he did not interfere in court decisions and that he had granted all extradition requests brought to his attention.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is being extradited for murder and aggravated assault, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
The Colom action is a governmental act that takes place when all judicial and constitutional means to convict the former President of the State (2000-2004) have been exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited once his legal status in Guatemala is clarified and his human rights guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of embezzling 120 million quetzal at the Ministry of Defense during his administration, a trial that preceded extradition, but the minister appealed and reopened the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organization was set up to prevent the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of the Trinijove social aid organisation have produced important results: in this quarter of a century, 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion have been helped to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, over a hundred jobs have been created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event was held yesterday at the former Fabra i Coats factory, attended by over 300 people.
Trinijove was set up in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems and at risk of being marginalized.
The celebration in Sant Andreu yesterday was attended by many officials from institutions that have worked with the association for 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different political orientations in election campaigns demonstrated the impartiality of Trinijove's work.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and then left-green city councillor Ricard Goma attended the celebrations.
The great Fabra i Coats hall was also visited by the current Catalan Minister for Social Affairs and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director-General of the Social Work Department of the La Caixa Savings Bank, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was set up in very difficult times and that the times are no less complicated today, but added that the work done so far "is a good foundation".
The President of the Generalitat sees Trinijove as a role model who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does", he explained.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The owners occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Rue Balmes, Barcelona.
The 12 squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house at number 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building they were illegally occupying yesterday at noon, where they had organized huge parties that had driven the neighborhood to despair.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be controlled", the manager confirmed.
The squatters, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest were occupied - took all the electrical equipment and some of the water supply, painted the walls, and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held on the three lower floors, lasting up to two days, driving tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a disco, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had fallen by 80% since the occupation began.
The owner of the disco pointed out that the occupants were unfairly competing, as they sold the drinks for three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the disco.
The owner of the club had also been reported by neighbours for disturbing the peace, while according to her the noise was not from the visitors to the disco but from the occupants and especially from the guests of the parties that were organized there, which according to the angry neighbours had become more and more prolonged in recent weeks.
The manager of the disco explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the building owner not to pay rent for the past nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (city police) also confirmed that it had received more complaints from neighbours in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in Barcelona's city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, last week called for the building to be evacuated immediately and for the problems of civil coexistence and the decline of the district to be taken care of.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in the past few months the squatters had entered all floors of the building and almost all apartments.
In this regard, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to crack down on the antisocial acts in the building".
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was evacuated by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., police approached 35 Montréal Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people trying to break into the building.
The four were arrested immediately.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree to the tender, aside from the disputes over the fees.
The municipal tender for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), the administration published its defamation of the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It has even been compared in numbers to New York's Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park became again the upper limit of Barcelona in the eyes of many, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in a north-south direction, but up (mountains) and down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone, with wild boars playing the role of the Yogi Bear.
This was the case when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for additional gates to Collserola.
No doubt a gate is a nod to the concept of a park.
Either that or someone's planning to put gates on the land.
The question is obvious: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for tenders is the talk of all Barcelona architects, not only from an organisational point of view but also in terms of reflection on the city.
It's almost a recurring theme for two members of this old-fashioned caste who meet in the elevator.
And it is this very fact that provides the material for one of the rare matches between what three architects from Barcelona think about it and some university professors who applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The call is appropriate.
For Roldán, after the attack on the coast, it is "necessary" to talk about the "front on the mountain" if the speech of Ildefons Cerda about the green apples has not been delivered.
"It should be assumed that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
One of the reasons is that it's easy to access.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" is a "lexical trap": they must not be "considered as entrances to a park, but as boundaries of areas to be acted upon".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona, who have experience in urban planning, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The Committee of the Regions believes that the European Parliament should be given the opportunity to make a contribution to the debate on the future of the European Parliament.
The first fear is one's own limitation on what can be built.
"To limit something always means to set the next step", that is, to go beyond it.
"We need to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [referring to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM) ] can lead to a real disaster".
Modol, who is more specific, says that the Collserola side, which runs towards Vallesana, "cannot be understood as a park that does not run towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola which should not "go unnoticed", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving his body the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
He also notes that the mountain's proximity to the city is the guide that allows architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" that this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams set up ("just the right one", he says) "We architects should be just a tool".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, since the tender conditions do not give a global view of Collserola: "There were 16 cross-sectional tenders", he says, "on the mountain-sea axis.
This has, in his case at least, led to him taking part in all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the programme and definition of a gate project would conflict with that of the architect of the gate next door.
He felt that it was essential for the city to ensure that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt was designed along its entire length to provide a smooth transition between the city and the green areas.
Casino forgives Jonas Larrazábal, who is released
After 72 days of silence, the Casino Red's representative has cleared the brother of the mayor of Monterrey of the charges of alleged extortion.
After 72 days in custody, Manuel Jonas Larrazábal is released after the representative of the Casino Red pardoned him before the Second Criminal Court of the District, which is prosecuting the brother of the mayor of Monterrey for extortion.
After the Casino Royale bombing, Sergio Gil García, the owner of Casino Red, released a series of photos and videos showing Manuel Jonás allegedly forcing him to pay a sum of money to get the city to approve the secret operation of the casino.
Following the criminal complaint, the prosecutor's office opened a criminal case against the brother of the Panista mayor, who was detained for 30 days on September 2.
After four hours with the official of the Ministerio Público 3 en Delitos Patrimoniales, he was taken to Casa de Arraigo 1 in the Barrio Antiguo of the capital.
He remained there for 49 days after a second arrest warrant was issued after the official of the Ministerio Público dismissed the charges of bribery and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to Cadereyta Prison for allegedly bribing the owners of Casino Red with one and a half million pesos, but he only stayed in the medium security zone for a few hours because of death threats.
The authorities allowed him to attend the trial as an inmate of the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was served with a warrant by the secretary of the Second District Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who found that after nearly two months of investigation, there was enough evidence to convict Jonas of paying 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the bookmaker in exchange for opening it.
This Monday, the commissioner of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, asked Judge José Luis Pecina, the mayor's brother, to commute the sentence, and he will be released in the next few hours.
During the hearing, Ramiro Arias, an official of the Ministry of Public Affairs assigned to the court, asked García Gómez if he had repaired the damage and which of the bookmaker's owners had pardoned him.
According to case 197/2011, Jonás Larrazábal is acquitted and there are no further appeals and no claims for damages.
After the bookie's representative was questioned at about 3:50 p.m., Larrazabal Breton was released immediately.
The clerk of the court, Jorge Yánez, went to the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonas that he had been acquitted and that his case was being filed.
He also informed him of the court order for his immediate release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven others.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes (SCT) of Mexico informed that the results of the investigation into the accident that killed the Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people indicate that the helicopter, with its entire intact structure, crashed directly into the ground without the pilot being able to make an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome,secretary of communications and transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight before takeoff.
"The fact that the propeller wings made contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing its fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had several ground contacts".
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers and therefore fulfilled all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
He also said that the examinations in the area where the plane landed did not find any helicopter parts.
"The search found no aircraft parts in other locations, the impact was on the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers and therefore met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
The priority now is to get the results as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat of Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter of the Estado Mayor Presidencial was travelling at cruising speed when it hit and the aircraft had fallen to a soft slope.
'This information supports the belief that this was a normal flight operation at the time of impact.'
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be taken into account in the investigation:
I 'm on the ground .
In accordance with flight regulations, this was a flight under the rules of sight flight, which means that the crew would have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded favorable weather conditions at the time of launch, and some low-hanging clouds formed during the flight toward the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico.
Selected routes:
It is possible that the crew had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Location of impact:
The impact coordinates and the helicopter's last radar record match, and there may have been no loss of control of the aircraft or deviation from the flight path prior to the impact.
Dispersion of the aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter was struck from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft debris suggests that the helicopter was struck by the ground with its structure intact.
No sign of fire or explosion.
The remains of the plane at the crash site suggest neither fire nor explosion.
The latest results indicate multiple ground contacts.
The on-site investigation found aircraft parts at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is steep and has an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence where the helicopter probably broke down.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a thorough search of an area beyond the crash site's restricted area, no scattered aircraft parts were found, reinforcing the belief that the intact aircraft structure had impacted the ground.
MSS announces research protocol to find the gene for obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexican Social Security Institute) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity, entitled "Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity", to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit (Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The public is invited to participate in the study, and those interested can come to the IMSS sports fields in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out on children and adolescents every Saturday from 8 a.m. onwards.
He stressed that the investigation started at Cuauhtémoc stadium in the west of Mexico and has been ongoing since 8 October at Nezahualcóyolt stadium in the east of Mexico.
Once the target of 500 to 600 subjects has been reached, the study will continue at the Independencia sports ground (south of the capital district) and conclude at the Morelos (north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for chronic degenerative diseases in Mexican children and adolescents.
On World Diabetes Day, he said the aim was for 3,000 children and adolescents aged six to 14 to complete nutrition questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also said that on the Saturdays mentioned, subjects would be measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure checked, and blood values such as glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study was being carried out in response to healthcare workers' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, the percentage of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls by 47 percent, and overweight has also increased dramatically", the IMSS specialist stressed.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the Mexican population is different from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
More generally, he explained, the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn off excess energy (calories) that we take in, so that it is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants would be a comprehensive study of the children to determine whether they had a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even look for dark skin wrinkles in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of pre-diabetes and metabolic disorders.
All information would be kept confidential and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors, who would explain all the results to the parents and suggest lifestyle changes that would be appropriate to prevent illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that contribute to obesity, obesity, and other chronic diseases: lack of physical activity, spending most of the day in front of the TV, and using transportation instead of walking.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with high fat and protein intake, and the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM, has developed polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather and temperature changes.
If the signs from the pavement were heeded, the need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes would not be needed when the rainy season begins in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, assuring that if the asphalt was properly laid and maintained, the number of potholes would be greatly reduced or even avoided.
In his lecture on "Hot Potholes from a Technical Point of View", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is in charge of is developing polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the pavement and thus prevent the appearance of potholes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltenes - and the other part a low molecular weight - the so-called malthenes.
The elasticity of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, is very tough at 120°C and almost solid at 50°C, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the strength of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes on a given day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations", explained the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City have a flexible pavement composed of six layers of material, the last three of which include asphalt.
Between the top layers is a layer of asphalt, made up of small stones that have been bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles are moving on it and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the pavement.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even more distributed", said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer", he explained, "a final layer is laid, the so-called carry layer, which is made of tiny stones, i.e., sand that has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, it requires a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and must produce friction.
This pavement receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs to be of an appropriate thickness and the material of which it is made must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature variations, are other important factors to consider, especially water", he said, "because it significantly affects the wear layer's behaviour.
When the terrain becomes wet, water enters the layer and only with difficulty comes out, causing all layers of the pavement to soften and, as a result, potholes to form.
"When a hole is created", he said, "the first thing that happens is that the roof layer wears off, and then the wear layer is affected, but the damage is not immediate, but a process that would have to be maintained at the first sign of damage by appropriate maintenance programs".
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico's National Research System) explained that vehicle load is another important cause of potholes, so the thickness of each layer of pavement must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and that this rule must be ensured to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that much research was still to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and which allow the potholes to be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
What was missing from the del Valle candidate to be the new Miss Colombia?
An analysis of the factors that contributed to Melina Ramírez Serna not being crowned Miss Colombia.
El Valle wins his 14th title.
Once again, Valle del Cauca was empty at the Miss Colombia pageant.
This time, Melina Ramírez Serna had to be content to stand on the winning podium, displaying a silver crown and the ribbon that identifies her as the new Miss Colombia.
The result obtained that night in Cartagena, where Miss Atlántico took the crown and the cedar, brings the Department to 14 mistitles and Melina joins the legion of women from Valle del Cauca who had almost held the crown in their hands.
The big question many people ask today is, what was missing?
Because the result is the decline of a great favorite who had shown at every show that she had everything to be the new Miss Colombia, not for nothing she had been chosen by Vogue as the Queen of the Police and Major Rostro Jolie, titles that had also been awarded to the beauty queens Taliana Vargas and Natalia Navarro, who took home the crown of Miss Colombia.
The first factor that was considered decisive for the jury's decision to nominate her as First Miss was that she was not convinced by the answer to the question "What book has influenced you the most and why?" asked by Martín Murillo Gómez of the Carreta Literaria Leamos.
The young woman from Valle del Cauca answered the questioner:
"I read a lot, I believe in literature, I think it's a way of civilization, and ultimately I think the book that has most influenced my childhood is The Little Prince, a very profound book.
I'm currently reading Guilt and Atonement, a book of universal culture that we should all read, and I'm reading a book by Irene Nemirovsky, a Russian woman, a beautiful book called Passions.
A response that met with little resistance, first because of the term 'civilizing' and second because she had not explicitly explained how each book she mentioned had influenced her.
But after the ceremony, Melina said she felt calm and happy with the result: "The universe is wise, it happens what has to happen.
And for all of you, please read The Little Prince.
Among other things, it's said that El Valle's favorite has burned out.
A journalist from Bogota suggested that the fact that she was the favorite, the one who received the most applause and had received all the prizes in advance (Easter gastronomy competition, audience vote for the best handmade costume and Reina Madre) "had made the other candidates jealous, which stressed the queen, who could not shine on stage".
And you saw that on her first show in a bathing suit on the beach at the Hilton Hotel and her two elevators at the coronation.
Although she performed with confidence in both, she lacked the strength and momentum that the representatives of Magdalena and Atlántico showed.
Ariel Osorio, a journalist on the RCN program "Como en casa", said that Melina's being crowned Miss "shows that the candidate who wins the most prizes during the competition does not become queen after all".
And Valle ended up avoiding the press, which was a mistake.
Another hypothesis is that Valle failed to convince the jury of her interest in social work, which is ultimately the essence of the National Beauty Contest.
There must be a reason why, two days before the international jury was to meet, Lucy Doughty said they were looking for a woman who was committed to the social issues of her country.
"Beauty alone is not enough for a Miss Colombia, you have to look beyond the physical and focus on the social sensation, on the fact that she had already worked on projects before she entered the competition", she explained.
It's also been speculated that Valle had sinned with her derriere defects and the fibrosis that was noted in her stomach area, but that's contradictory, because the jury chose her as a candidate for "natural beauty" with a healthy body, good eating habits and responsible physical work.
The queens' coach, Jorge Hernán Orozco, admits that Melina did not have the best body, that there was no better, "but her problem with the abdominal fibrosis, which to be honest, was hardly noticeable to me, depressed her score on the last day".
Meanwhile, journalist Guido Hoyos of Cromos magazine feels that the Valle del Cauca woman's mistake was the surgery she had undergone.
"The surgeries are okay, but Valle didn't know how to get them done right.
Her body was never her strong point, and this job had to pay".
Because of this prize, which is awarded for the first time by the National Beauty Contest, after the performance in the bathing suit, a cruel prediction was made that was to come true at night.
Whether that's true or not, the fact is that Melina is entering her year of reign today, not as queen, but as princess, a position that will allow her to represent Colombia in one of the international beauty pageants upon nomination.
However, she will go down in history as one of the queens who, despite her stunning performance for Cartagena, missed the crown.
That was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A California lophoscopist went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4, a loboscopist from the Investigative Unit of the Public Prosecutor's Office (CTI) in Cali entered as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, was on call.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in Chocó communities, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the location of the bodies he was to identify.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses, he specialised in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the surfaces of the hands and feet.
During the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
He was on a helicopter from Palmyra to Cauca Friday night.
He knew he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who had led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was told to take the ten-finger print of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived at the location of the body with the examiner's aid, he could not identify the body because of its physical appearance, which bore no resemblance to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local peasant, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints are not lies.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell, and a flashlight, Eleazar compared the body's fingerprints with those found on the print sheet.
He saw it right: it was "Alfonso Cano".
