Moleskine, a trademark notebook. I'm going to need it.
Launched by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair for adventure, candlelight hours spent writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable again, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the egg-colored pages, as if aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, who was then the company's technical adviser, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique called mole skin, which refers to a cotton lacquer used for upholstery, for example.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
The success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12,7 million units.
This is a far cry from the usual production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a fantasy picture of the buyers, since the notebook is equally appealing to businessmen, students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of a cosmopolitan, cultured, open-minded client.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now has more than 100 employees and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on Internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in city centres and is keen to assert its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of the times and its new need for writing, which persists despite the boom in e-mail", explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural character is accompanied by the development of Moleskine: recently the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour", in which architects and artists displayed their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard-patterned cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and managed to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand has the full range of items.
A success that makes anyone envious: In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, opening a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate for disabled people remain so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today marks the beginning of the 15th week of work for the disabled.
Despite a targeted publicity policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is still twice the average: 19% as against 9% for the general population.
Discouraged?
"No", emphasizes Éric Blanchet, director general of the association Adapt, which organises the 'Work Week for the Disabled.'"
"Progress has been made in fifteen years".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times as high".
"Nevertheless, there is still a tremendous amount of work to be done".
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they can find a job.
The elderly are more likely to be affected: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with higher education degrees.
Finally, longterm unemployment is also very high: 53% for the disabled compared with 38% for the general population.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the workforce, and that are "the core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the brakes.
What remains is the unspoken, the attitudes that are certain but slow to develop.
A study conducted in April by the IMS entrepreneurs' association for La Cité magazine indicated that managers surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabled people" who are "overrepresented" by "people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled".
The result is that private enterprises with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to meet the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, which date from 2008, refer to a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organisation responsible for collecting contributions from companies that break the law.
The evidence: the number of 'fee-paying' establishments and the sum of the amounts paid fell between 2007 and 2011, falling in numbers from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, put a lot of pressure on companies", explained Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real learning curve, especially for large groups of companies".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
